description.plain:
Rodrick Wayne Moore, Jr. (b. October 22, 1998), known professionally as Roddy Ricch, is a recording artist, songwriter, and record producer from Compton, California.

On November 22, 2017, Roddy released his first mixtape, Feed Tha Streets. The mixtape was succeeded Feed Tha Streets II, released in November 2018, which includes his breakout hit singles “Die Young” and “Every Season.”

Over the years, Roddy has gained co-signs and features from Meek Mill, on “Splash Warning” in November 2018, and now-deceased Nipsey Hussle, on “Racks in the Middle,” in February 2019, the latter in which earnt Roddy his first Grammy win with the Best Rap Performance Award. He has also worked with artists such as Post Malone, on the “Wow.” remix, in March 2019, and Rich The Kid, on “Go Up,” in July 2019. Roddy is currently signed to Bird Vision Entertainment and Atlantic Records.

In June 2019, Roddy appeared on American record producer Mustard’s third studio album, Perfect Ten, on “Ballin',”, which ultimately reached the Top 20 of the Billboard Hot 100 Chart and received over three nominations at the 62nd Annual Grammy Awards.

On December 6, 2019, Roddy released his major-label debut studio album under Atlantic Records, Please Excuse Me for Being Antisocial, supported by three singles, October 2019’s “Big Stepper” and “Start wit Me,”, the latter featuring Gunna, and “Tip Toe”, featuring A Boogie wit da Hoodie. The debut was a runaway success, leading to Roddy to pick up the Favourite Hip-Hop/Rap Album Award at the 2020 American Music Awards, as well as Album of the Year at the 2020 Apple Music Awards and the 2020 BET Hip Hop Awards.

“The Box” became the breakout hit from the album. Thanks to the massive popularity, mostly coming from the TikTok memes, the track reached number-one on the Billboard Hot 100 in January 2020, as well as peaking at number two on the UK Singles Chart. The single went on to become 8x Certified Platinum in January 2021, before rapidly surpassing 10 million sales in the and becoming Certified Diamond in December 2021. The track earnt Roddy Song of the Year Awards at the 2020 BET Hip Hop Awards and 2020 Apple Music Award, as well as a nomination at the 63rd Grammy Awards. The single Because of the boosting recognition of “The Box,” “High Fashion,” Roddy’s second collaboration with Mustard, has also found its place in the Hot 100’s top forty.

Following a one year hiatus, on June 4, 2021, Roddy returned with the sombre melodic ballad “late at night”. On December 17th, Roddy dropped his much anticipated sophomore studio album LIVE LIFE FAST. The album came with mixed reviews with many not commending the artistic direction he tried to take the project. Following up to 2022, Roddy deactivated his socials amidst backlash on a snippet he released to battle LLF’s poor review.

He bounced back in June 2022 with an EP titled The Big 3 which worked as a precursor to his third commercial mixtape in which he teased months prior. Roddy began the mixtape rollout in September with tracks such as “Ghetto Superstar”, “Stop Breathing” and “Aston Martin Truck”, later announcing that Feed Tha Streets III will be released in November 2022.

description.plain:
“The Box” has seen massive success since its release—it peaked at number one on the Billboard Hot 100, beating Justin Bieber’s single “Yummy” by one spot and marking Roddy’s first number one hit on the chart. The track received a boost in popularity when several TikTok videos and memes parodied the production, which helped Roddy’s debut studio album, Please Excuse Me for Being Antisocial, reach the number one spot on Billboard’s Top 200 Albums in December 2019.

Atlantic Records A&R Keefa Black confirmed on Twitter that the unique squeaking sounds that make up the entire track were recorded by Roddy after the song was complete. Producer 30 Roc further recalled how the track came together in an interview with Genius News:

 When it came down to ‘The Box,’ for me, it was just like, let’s see if we can push him outside of his range. I really didn’t think he was going to do it. […] Then [Roddy] came and he was like, ‘EHH ERR, EHH ERR,’ and we all looked at each other…

songs.full_title: High Fashion by Roddy Ricch (Ft. Mustard)
songs.title: High Fashion

description.plain:
In “High Fashion,” Roddy Ricch uses a smooth, laid-back delivery to list an extensive inventory of luxury status symbols.  Though he insists he “ain’t no player,” he also brags that he has a collection of women, and hopes that displaying his wealth in this way will persuade the object of the song to join it as his “Prada Bae.”

The song is the 11th track on Roddy’s debut album and his second collaboration with Mustard, after his feature on June, 2019’s “Ballin'.”
